@node what_is_this "What is this?"

    (¯`·._.·' Showmodule GUI Mega Webber `·._.·'¯)


             (_.·'¯ What is this? ¯`·._)

Content:

 @{" 1 " LINK what_is_this 15} The name
 @{" 2 " LINK what_is_this 44} What's so good about this GUI?




@{u}The name@{uu}

  Showmodule GUI Mega Webber - what a ridiculous name!!!

  Well, I shall give you a brief name-explanation first!!

  In the beginning there was no shell for Showmodule,
  this annoyed me a little... Cuz' it was no fun to
  write a command line with path and stuff all the time!!

  So, I made misc scripts (no GUI, though) to make the
  Showmodule life simpler!

  After a while I learned how to use gadtools, so then I
  made my first Showmodule GUI (as I called it back then).
  I made several versions (you can get those + sources
  at the smgmw homepage). Many times I gave up, and began yet
  another version... With new design etc. So the source was
  named showmodulegui.e, and I didn't want to delete it... so
  I saved the new source as "showmoduleguim.e", where the "m"
  character just was a... letter to separate the names!!!

  Then I took that "m" and made it into "Mega"!!!

  And when I added the "links" function, I also added
  the Webber part to the name!!



@{u}What is so good about this GUI??@{uu}

  The GUI is (as you might have noticed?) divided into
  two listviews (and some other gadgets..).

  The left contains what I like to call anchors!
  These are stuff like OBJECTS, LIBRARY, CONST,
  DEFINE and DEF variables.

  This will make it easier to find the anchor
  you're looking for since you get all of them
  in a list, not seing the anchor contents.

  When you press an anchor, its content will be
  listed in the right listview. :)

  The active line can also be copied into the clipboard
  by a simple key-combination or a quick menu visit.


  And do not forget the fact that you can search for
  variables in the module too!!

  @{fg shine}links links links @{fg text}@{b}LINKS@{ub}@{fg shine} links links links@{fg text}

  Another thing is the "Links" function.
  If you press a string in the right listview
  you can be linked to an other module!!

  Let's say you press:
    @{i}(  90)   windowport:PTR TO mp@{ui}

  Then the module 'exec/ports.m' will be loaded into the
  program, and the "OBJECT mp" anchor will be visible.

  The links are of course editable, so that you can make
  whatever links you want!!


  @{fg shine}aliases alises aliases @{fg text}@{b}ALIASES@{ub}@{fg shine} alises aliases aliases@{fg text}

  You can for example write "i/i", and the module
  emodules:intuition/intuition.m will be loaded!!!

  Also the aliases are editable.

@endnode
